  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- International standards for preventing money laundering\n- Established in 1989\n- Sets global guidelines for financial institutions\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Adopted in 2000\n- Provides framework for international cooperation against money laundering\n\n3. The Palermo Convention\n- Requires countries to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international legal cooperation\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision guidelines\n- Provides recommendations for bank regulations\n- Helps prevent financial crimes\n\n5. EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establishes regulations for member states\n- Requires strict reporting and monitoring of financial transactions\n\nMost countries have national laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement anti-money laundering compliance programs\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
